      "content": `Cursor and Windsurf represent the new generation of AI-native code editors — tools built from the ground up around AI assistance rather than bolted onto traditional IDEs.\n\n## Quick Verdict\n\n- **Choose Cursor if:** Multi-file editing and flexible model selection are important to you.\n- **Choose Windsurf if:** You want an agent mode that can tackle complex multi-file tasks autonomously.\n\n## Multi-File Editing\n\nBoth editors excel at editing code across multiple files simultaneously. Cursor's multi-file editing is its killer feature — describe a change and it plans and implements it across your codebase.\n\nWindsurf's agent mode goes further, autonomously planning and executing complex development tasks. It can debug, refactor, and build features with minimal human direction.\n\n## Model Flexibility\n\nCursor lets you choose from multiple AI models (including your own API keys), giving you control over cost, speed, and quality tradeoffs.\n\nWindsurf uses Codeium's proprietary models, which are optimized for code understanding but offer less flexibility.\n\n## IDE Compatibility\n\nBoth are built on VS Code forks, providing excellent extension compatibility. Cursor has been around longer and has a more mature extension ecosystem.\n\n## Pricing\n\nBoth offer generous free tiers with paid plans for power users. Cursor's pricing is slightly more transparent.\n\n## Bottom Line\n\nCursor is the more mature, flexible choice. Windsurf's agent mode is more ambitious and shows promise for the future of autonomous coding.`
